# Puzzles.elm

The Puzzles gallery's top-level Elm app. Renders a vertical
gallery of curated LynRummy puzzle panels, each embedding an
independent `Main.Play` instance so Steve plays multiple
puzzles on one scrolling page.

## Status

- **Label:** production (puzzle gallery, per ENTRY_POINTS.md).
  Originally a SPIKE for board-feel studies, the surface has
  matured into the curated gallery used to exercise the agent
  and capture conformance scenarios. Panels auto-create their
  puzzle session on page load and swap straight to the Play
  surface when the session id returns. No Play button; no
  single-active gating. DOM-id collisions for hand-card
  replay are a known limitation (see below).

## Shape

Lab keeps a `Dict String Panel` keyed by puzzle title.
Each Panel cycles `Creating → Playing Model` (or
`Creating → Failed reason` on server error). Msg routing
uses `PlayMsg title pmsg` so a drag in panel A never
touches panel B's Model.

Subscriptions fan out via `Sub.batch`: every Playing
panel contributes its own `Play.subscriptions`. Elm
deduplicates Browser.Events subscriptions by source, so
e.g. one onMouseMove sub is shared across panels; the
dispatch splits via the wrapped `PlayMsg title` tag.

Multi-active coexistence is safe for live play: board
DOM ids are per-gameId via `State.boardDomIdFor`. Hand
card DOM ids are NOT per-gameId; that matters only when
Instant Replay is used inside a panel (AnimateMergeHand's
Browser.Dom.getElement). For live gesture capture
(what Lab is for), hand cards identify by mouse click
coordinates, not DOM id — so the collision is harmless.

## Puzzle catalog

Five panels today, each defined as an Elm literal:

1. **Pair peel**
2. **Tight right edge** — forces a MoveStack before a
   hand-card merge due to bounds overflow
3. **Split for set** — mid-run extraction
4. **Peel for run** — peel from a 4-set
5. **Follow-up merge (chained runs)** — primary merge
   plus a stack-to-stack follow-up

The catalog is currently embedded in Lab.elm. Planned
move: pull from Python's `puzzles.py` as canonical source
(with a build step that writes a JSON catalog and a Go
endpoint serving it) so agent-runs and human-runs on the
same named puzzle can be correlated in SQLite.

## Dependencies

- `Main.Play` — the embeddable component (Browser symlink
  at `src/Game` replaced by source-directory sharing in
  `elm.json`: `../../elm/src` is a second source root).
- `Main.State`, `Main.Msg` — via re-export.
- `Game.Card`, `Game.CardStack`, `Game.Hand` — domain types
  used when constructing Demo literals.

